keyDetails.content:
Boundary-fill is a recursive pixel-filling algorithm used to color a bounded region in the frame buffer. It starts at an interior 'seed' point (x, y) and recursively paints pixels outward until it hits a specified boundary color.

Mathematical Pseudocode:
void boundaryFill(int x, int y, int fill_color, int border_color) {
  int current = getPixel(x, y);
  if (current != border_color && current != fill_color) {
    setPixel(x, y, fill_color);
    boundaryFill(x + 1, y, fill_color, border_color); // Right
    boundaryFill(x - 1, y, fill_color, border_color); // Left
    boundaryFill(x, y + 1, fill_color, border_color); // Up
    boundaryFill(x, y - 1, fill_color, border_color); // Down
  }
}

Flood-fill is used when we want to replace an entire connected area of an original target color with a new color. Instead of stopping at a boundary color, it checks if the current pixel matches the original target 'old' color.

Mathematical Pseudocode:
void floodFill(int x, int y, int old_color, int new_color) {
  if (getPixel(x, y) == old_color) {
    setPixel(x, y, new_color);
    floodFill(x + 1, y, old_color, new_color); // Right
    floodFill(x - 1, y, old_color, new_color); // Left
    floodFill(x, y + 1, old_color, new_color); // Up
    floodFill(x, y - 1, old_color, new_color); // Down
  }
}
